## 4. Why "Multiple `SELECT`" (i.e., multiple independent result sets) Don't Work in One CTE Statement

This is a common confusion point. Key facts:

- A **single CTE block** can contain only **one `SELECT` statement** as its defining query (except recursive CTEs, which combine exactly two parts via `UNION ALL`: anchor + recursive member).
- You **cannot** do:
  ```sql
  WITH cte1 AS (
      SELECT * FROM a;
      SELECT * FROM b;   -- ❌ invalid — two SELECTs, no UNION combining them
  )
  ```
  Because a CTE definition must evaluate to **one single tabular result** — SQL requires a single, unambiguous logical result set to bind the name `cte1` to. Two unrelated `SELECT`s have no defined way to merge into one named object.
- To combine multiple result sets under one CTE, you must explicitly use a set operator (`UNION`, `UNION ALL`, `INTERSECT`, `EXCEPT`) so the two SELECTs become **one logical result**:
  ```sql
  WITH cte1 AS (
      SELECT * FROM a
      UNION ALL
      SELECT * FROM b
  )
  SELECT * FROM cte1;
  ```
- If you want **multiple independent named result sets**, you must declare **multiple separate CTEs** (comma-separated, one `SELECT` each), not multiple `SELECT`s inside one:
  ```sql
  WITH cte1 AS (SELECT * FROM a),
       cte2 AS (SELECT * FROM b)
  SELECT * FROM cte1 JOIN cte2 ON ...;
  ```
- Also — the **outer/final statement** after all CTEs can only be **one statement** (`SELECT`, or in some engines `INSERT`/`UPDATE`/`DELETE`/`MERGE` using the CTE) — you can't chain multiple final statements off one `WITH`.

**Underlying reason**: A CTE is a *name bound to a single relation (table expression)* — SQL's relational model requires every named expression to resolve to exactly one schema (fixed set of columns/types). Multiple unrelated SELECTs would produce ambiguous/undefined shape for that name, so the grammar disallows it outright (parse-time error, not a runtime one).

